pr_body:
Still missing for feature parity with the CMake build:
- Disabling plugins.
- Detecting versions of libsoup.
- Detecting versions of gstreamer.
- Selecting media types for gstreamer.
- Building tests.

I think this could be merged on its own, however.

pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 1288855971, 'comment_body': 'This is not strictly speaking needed. The dependency lookup uses the value in the .wrap file. `override_dependency` is only used in special cases (e.g. when package `foo` provides an unrelated dependency `bar` and you want that to be used as opposed to the original library that provides `bar`).', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 8, 9, 16, 21, 35, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jpakkane', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1288868618, 'comment_body': "IMHO using `meson.override_dependency()` and remove variable name from wrap file is generally best practice. However WrapDB is a bit an exception because we actually control both the wrap file and the `meson.build`, so we can guarantee they use the same variable name. That's not the case when `meson.build` is upstream.

The downside of adding `meson.override_dependency()` is it requires Meson 0.54 which could be newer than what the project would normally require. But 0.54 is pretty old nowadays.

In this specific case, gee.wrap has `dependency_names = gee-0.8` so override_dependency is required, or it should be changed to `gee-0.8 = gee_dep`. Not sure how that passed the CI, I thought we were checking for that.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 8, 9, 16, 32, 56, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'xclaesse', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1288880145, 'comment_body': "In the [Wrap dependency system manual](https://mesonbuild.com/Wrap-dependency-system-manual.html), I read:
> **This mechanism assumes the subproject calls `meson.override_dependency('foo-1.0', foo_dep)` so Meson knows which dependency object should be used as fallback.** Since that method was introduced in version 0.54.0, as a transitional aid for projects that do not yet make use of it the variable name can be provided in the wrap file with entries in the format foo-1.0 = foo_dep.
> For example when using a recent enough version of glib that uses meson.override_dependency() to override glib-2.0, gobject-2.0 and gio-2.0, a wrap file would look like:
>
> ```
> [wrap-git]
> url=https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/glib.git
> revision=glib-2-62
> depth=1
>
> [provide]
> dependency_names = glib-2.0, gobject-2.0, gio-2.0
> ```
>
> With older version of glib dependency variable names need to be specified:
>
> ```
> [wrap-git]
> url=https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/glib.git
> revision=glib-2-62
> depth=1
>
> [provide]
> glib-2.0=glib_dep
> gobject-2.0=gobject_dep
> gio-2.0=gio_dep
> ```

This sounds to me like the call is supposed to be there.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 8, 9, 16, 39, 10, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'hrxi', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1288882039, 'comment_body': '> Not sure how that passed the CI, I thought we were checking for that.

Ah! missing from releases.json, so it did not get tested at all! Which explains why locally this wrap fails immediately with `ERROR: Target 'gee-0.8' has 1 outputs: ['libgee-0.8.a'], but only 4 "install_dir"s were found.`.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 8, 9, 16, 39, 50, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'xclaesse', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1288929614, 'comment_body': '```suggestion
      "0.20.6-1"
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 8, 9, 17, 14, 2, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'xclaesse', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1288951134, 'comment_body': 'Thanks!', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 8, 9, 17, 33, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'hrxi', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1290067373, 'comment_body': "TBH, I'm frustrated that it still try to build on platforms we explicitly say won't work. @eli-schwartz forced adding that but I disagree, we just end up adding all kind of reasons here and waste time on it every time a new reason appears. Anyway... I guess that's fine...", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 8, 10, 12, 42, 38, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'xclaesse', 'type': 'User'}]

I also don't think .patch files are going to be included into wrapdb releases, so that won't work.

IMHO you could just skip tests. When the Meson port is upstream, we don't need to be their CI.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 9, 12, 14, 12, 29, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'xclaesse', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1323156943, 'comment_body': "It sounds like the policy is suboptimal in this case, where it leads to not running the tests at all vs simply excluding one known-to-be-bad test.

I can also include the whole test file from the meson.build if that's better, it wouldn't be patching source code.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 9, 12, 14, 44, 42, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'hrxi', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1323158987, 'comment_body': 'Sounds good.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 9, 12, 14, 46, 3, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'hrxi', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1323221337, 'comment_body': "In this case running unit tests is just a waste of CI time, we just distribute upstream package as-is. Running tests makes sense when we maintain the Meson port in WrapDB because we have to make sure our build actually works. IMHO the bug is reported upstream, now it's not our problem anymore.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 9, 12, 15, 29, 27, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'xclaesse', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1323282980, 'comment_body': "> IMHO the bug is reported upstream, now it's not our problem anymore.

As an aside: Why does wrapdb default to running the tests if it's mostly a waste of CI time?

", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 9, 12, 16, 18, 25, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'hrxi', 'type': 'User'}]

This will change the order of system include directories to be the same as other include directories, most importantly placing the build directory before the source directory.

Fixes #11637.

pr_title: Check for Windows using `_WIN32` instead of `_WINDOWS`
pr_body:
`_WINDOWS` isn't guaranteed to be defined when building for Windows.

https://stackoverflow.com/q/73705992

Additionally, `#include <WinBase.h>` is unnecessary; `#include <Windows.h>` already covers it.

https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/desktop/legacy/aa366877(v=vs.85)
